e.g. ->
i/p -> [[1, 2],[1, 4],[3, 4]]
sort -> [[1, 4],[1, 2],[3, 4]]

i/p->[[1, 4],[3, 6],[2, 8]]
sort -> [[1, 4],[2, 8],[3, 6]]

i/p -> [[3, 11],[5, 12],[4, 10]]
sort-> [[3, 11],[4, 10],[5, 12]]

so by this we can see if current element start<=next element start and current element end>= next element end, consume it and increment counter to indicate one element is deleted. as soon as above condition met try to consume as many as we can.
basically check how many elements we can consume with in current element start and end boundary.
now after first iteration we have consumed what max possible. now again repeat same step for next current element start and end.
```
public int removeCoveredIntervals(int[][] intervals) {
		Arrays.sort(intervals, this::compare);
		int i = 0;
		//counter to store deleted elements count.
		int c = 0;
		//iterate every element
		while (i < intervals.length) {
		//set current element as min and max
			int min = intervals[i][0];
			int max = intervals[i][1];
			//check how many elements we can consume with in current min and max
			while (i < intervals.length - 1 && min <= intervals[i + 1][0] && max >= intervals[i + 1][1]) {
				c++;
				i++;
			}
			i++;
		}
		//return length of new array after deletion.
		return intervals.length - c;
	}
	//sort
	private int compare(int[] a, int[] b) {
		if (a[0] == b[0]) {
			return b[1] - a[1];
		}
		return a[0] - b[0];
	}
