**With sorting**:

Sorting makes it obvious that we get smallest intervals first and just keep mapping the previous big interval and the current interval to get the solution.
```
class Solution {
    static class Data{
        int x,y;
        Data(int x,int y){
            this.x = x;
            this.y = y;
        }
    }
    public int removeCoveredIntervals(int[][] intervals) {
        Data[] d = new Data[intervals.length];
        for(int i=0;i<intervals.length;++i) d[i] = new Data(intervals[i][0],intervals[i][1]);
        Arrays.sort(d,new Comparator<Data>(){
            public int compare(Data d1,Data d2){
                if(d1.x < d2.x) return -1;
                if(d2.x < d1.x) return 1;
                return -1 * (d1.y - d2.y);
            }
        });

        int rem = 1,prev = 0;

        for(int i=1;i<d.length;++i){
            if(d[i].x >= d[prev].x && d[i].y <= d[prev].y) continue;
            prev = i;
            rem++;
        }

        return rem;
    }
}
```

**Without Sorting:**

* We can make use of the constraints `0 <= intervals[i][0] < intervals[i][1] <= 10^5` a bit.
* Every interval has a start and an end.
* In this approach, we map the start with it's best end.
* So for example, for `[[1,4],[3,6],[2,8],[1,20]]`, the table(as in `pairs` array) would look like:

   * 1 => 20
   * 2 => 8
   * 3 => 6
* Now, we just percolate down from `1` to `3` keeping the best end at hand.
* In the above example, we keep `20` with us first. Since it annihilates everything, it is the only interval that remains. 
* If we get a new end greater than the current one, we update the `prev` in the below code accordingly.
```
class Solution {
    public int removeCoveredIntervals(int[][] intervals) {
       int[] pairs = new int[100001];
       int start = -1,end = -1;
       for(int i=0;i<intervals.length;++i){
           pairs[intervals[i][0]] = Math.max(pairs[intervals[i][0]],intervals[i][1]);
           if(start == -1 || start > intervals[i][0]) start = intervals[i][0];
           if(end == -1 || end < intervals[i][1]) end = intervals[i][1];
       } 

       int rem = 0,prev = 0;
       for(int i=start;i<=end;++i){
           if(pairs[i] > prev){
               rem++;
               prev = pairs[i];
           }
       } 

       return rem; 
    }
}
```

