solutions.content:
It is obvious that we will consider all the intervals with larger length before considering the shorter ones. Now we have two options, either to sort by the end time or start time. 

Let's sort by the end time. Consider you have intervals: `[[1,10],[3,4],[5,6],[1,2]]`
After sorting the intervals from end time our intervals array will be: `[[1,2],[3,4],[5,6],[1,10]]`
As we can see, our very last interval `[1,10]` covers all the intervals before it, but we wont be able to keep track of the interval it covers as it is the last element in the array, hence we discard sorting by end time. ( There might be a solution which sorts by end time, so if you have come across one feel free to share) 

Let's sort by start time. Considering the same intervals, After sorting by start time we will have `[[1,2],[1,10],[3,4],[5,6]]`
Now as we can see `[1,2]` comes under `[1,10]` but for simplicity we will consider having `[1,10]` before `[1,2]` because it covers large interval length. Hence we will sort by start time first, in case the start time is equal we will have the larger end time first. So now our array will look something like:` [[1,10],[1,2],[3,4],[5,6]]`

We will take each interval one by one and see if it covers next one:

```
class Solution {
    public int removeCoveredIntervals(int[][] intervals) {
        if(intervals == null || intervals.length == 0) return 0;
        Arrays.sort(intervals, (i1,i2) -> (i1[0]==i2[0]?i2[1]-i1[1]:i1[0]-i2[0]));
        int c = intervals[0][0], d = intervals[0][1];
        int ans = intervals.length;
        for(int i=1;i<intervals.length;i++){
            int a = intervals[i][0], b = intervals[i][1];
            if(c<=a && b<=d) ans--; 
            else {
                c = a;
                d = b;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```

