**Idea:**
* The solution is pretty similar to that of [LC 56. Merge Intervals](https://leetcode.com/problems/merge-intervals/discuss/1645484/Java-or-Greedy-or-Simple-with-comments)
* Sort by start time
* Start remaining intervals with value = size(intervals), i.e. initially all intervals are remaining 
* For each interval pair, check if one is covered by the other. 
* If either covers the other then, then this interval will be used for the next iteration. Reduce remaining by 1
* Else the latter interval will be used for the next iteration

**Example:** [[1, 4],[3, 6],[2, 8]]
```
Sort by start = [[1, 4],[2, 8],[3, 6]]

prev = [1, 4], current = [2, 8], remaining = 3
neither covers the other, update prev = [2, 8], current = [3, 6]

prev = [2, 8], current = [3, 6], remaining = 3
prev covers current, remaining = 2

[Ans] 2
```
>**T/S:** O(n lg n)/O(n)
```
public int removeCoveredIntervals(int[][] intervals) {
	Arrays.sort(intervals, Comparator.comparingInt(i -> i[0]));
	var remaining = intervals.length;

	for (int i = 1, prev[] = intervals[0]; i < intervals.length; i++)
		if (prev[0] <= intervals[i][0] && intervals[i][1] <= prev[1]) {
			remaining--;
		} else {
			if (intervals[i][0] <= prev[0] && prev[1] <= intervals[i][1])
				remaining--;
			prev = intervals[i];
		}

	return remaining;
}
